            "answer_text": "Because it is. It's so elegant and graceful that the listener isn't conscious of the underlying complexity and sheer skill. A perfect example is the \u201cElvira Madigan\u201d theme from the slow movement of the Piano Concerto no 21 in C major KV467. To the casual listener, it might sound like a fairly straightforward, rather moody love theme. But that effect is achieved by complex harmonies, including some amazing modulations that would only have occurred to Mozart. And his music is full of moments like that. ",
